pullRequest.body:
We make `LocallyRingedSpace.Hom` (resp. `Scheme.Hom`) into a structure
instead of a subtype (resp. type-synonym of the former) to make clearer the
abstraction boundaries between them and presheafed spaces, which allow
us to remove some `erw`s.

Plus, this enables us to write `f.base` and `f.c` instead of `f.val.base` and `f.val.c`.


---

Modulo one last minor comment, LGTM, thanks a lot!
I'm not sure what the `simpVarHead` issue is. The head symbol doesn't seem like a variable to me and it fires correctly. If this is still bad I can turn on this lemma locally.
I made a few tests and I can confirm that the lemma triggers.
Is this auto-generated name `f.toHom_1` stable? If not, can we avoid it? `f.1` would also work.
I think this is quite stable. On a side note, do you think `Hom.val` should get a more descriptive name like `toLRSHom`?
I think `toLRSHom` is too long. Is `Hom.lrs` too cryptic? If not we could have `Hom.psh` for the underlying `Hom` of presheafed spaces.
I think the current design of the library shouldn't require user to use these type-cast that often so it's fine if it's a bit long?

Sounds reasonable, since `f.c` and `f.base` are directly accessible now, I have not checked in detail though how often the explicit cast is needed. Maybe we can replace `val` as you suggested by `toLRSHom` and add `toPSSHom` as `abbrev` for `toHom`. If it turns out to be annoying we can `sed` back quickly.
I am happy with the `val -> toLRSHom` and `toHom -> toShHom`.

  f.c.naturality i

Also above in `Hom.app`.

```suggestion
  haveI := PresheafedSpace.c_isIso_of_iso f.toHom
  NatIso.isIso_app_of_isIso f.c _
```
maybe? Not sure what the most readable form is for the underlying map of (pre)sheafed spaces. `f.toHom` is also not very telling, but `f.val.val` is longish.
similarly below

```suggestion
  LocallyRingedSpace.stalkMap_congr_hom f.val g.val congr($hfg.1) x
```
I think we should try to avoid `f.1` since it pretty-prints as `toHom_1` which is not very understandable. Or maybe we could make `f.1` pretty-print as `f.val`?
Should `X` and `Y` be implicit here?

```suggestion
lemma stalkMap_germ (U : Opens Y) (x : X) (hx : f.base x ‚àà U) :
    Y.presheaf.germ U (f.base x) hx ‚â´ f.stalkMap x =
      f.c.app (op U) ‚â´ X.presheaf.germ ((Opens.map f.base).obj U) x hx :=
  PresheafedSpace.stalkMap_germ f.toShHom U x hx
```

```suggestion
lemma stalkMap_germ_apply (U : Opens Y) (x : X) (hx : f.base x ‚àà U) (y) :
    f.stalkMap x (Y.presheaf.germ U (f.base x) hx y) =
      X.presheaf.germ ((Opens.map f.base).obj U) x hx (f.c.app (op U) y) :=
  PresheafedSpace.stalkMap_germ_apply f.toShHom U x hx y
```
I can't comment on unchanged code, but in `iff_isPreimmersion` and in `of_isPreimmersion` below there are two more `f.1.base` which should be `f.base`
In the definition of `IsPreimmersion` on the `base_embedding` field and in `Scheme.Hom.embedding`, there are two more `f.1.base`.
In `resLE_map` below, there is another `f.1.base`.

As with [CategoryTheory.Iso.commRingCatIsoToRingEquiv](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Category/Ring/Basic.html#CategoryTheory.Iso.commRingCatIsoToRingEquiv), this  could maybe be in the `CategoryTheory.Iso` namespace? E.g. `CategoryTheory.Iso.schemeIsoHomeo`.

I dunno. But I think it wouldn't cause much trouble here?
